.SH NAME
when \- convert timestamps between formats, apply time arithmetic, and
calculate durations
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]when\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[I]input\f[R]
[\f[I]+/\-offset\f[R]]
.PP
\f[B]when\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] \f[B]diff\f[R] \f[I]time1\f[R]
\f[I]time2\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
Converts timestamps between formats, applies time arithmetic, and
calculates durations.
Cross\-platform \(em fills the gap on Windows where no native date
conversion command exists.
.PP
Two modes of operation:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Conversion mode\f[R]: parse a timestamp, optionally apply an
offset, and output the result in all formats.
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]Diff mode\f[R]: calculate the duration between two timestamps.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\(entz\f[R] \f[I]ZONE\f[R]
Display in this timezone.
Accepts both IANA timezone IDs (e.g.\ \f[B]America/New_York\f[R]) and
Windows timezone IDs (e.g.\ \f[B]Eastern Standard Time\f[R]).
.TP
\f[B]\(enutc\f[R]
Output only the UTC ISO 8601 timestamp (conversion mode).
Useful for scripting and piping.
.TP
\f[B]\(enlocal\f[R]
Output only the local ISO 8601 timestamp (conversion mode).
When combined with \f[B]\(entz\f[R], uses the specified timezone instead
of the system local timezone.
.TP
\f[B]\(eniso\f[R]
Output only the ISO 8601 duration string (diff mode).
.TP
\f[B]\(enjson\f[R]
Output results as JSON to stdout.
.TP
\f[B]\(encolor\f[R][=\f[I]WHEN\f[R]]
Coloured output: auto (default when omitted), always, or never.
.TP
\f[B]\(enno\-color\f[R]
Disable coloured output.
.TP
\f[B]\(enversion\f[R]
Show version.
